Bank Churn Prediction

Problem Statement¶

Context¶

Businesses like banks which provide service have to worry about problem of 'Customer Churn' i.e. customers leaving and joining another service provider. It is important to understand which aspects of the service influence a customer's decision in this regard. Management can concentrate efforts on improvement of service, keeping in mind these priorities.

Objective¶

You as a Data scientist with the bank need to build a neural network based classifier that can determine whether a customer will leave the bank or not in the next 6 months.

Data Dictionary¶

  • CustomerId: Unique ID which is assigned to each customer

  • Surname: Last name of the customer

  • CreditScore: It defines the credit history of the customer.

  • Geography: A customer’s location

  • Gender: It defines the Gender of the customer

  • Age: Age of the customer

  • Tenure: Number of years for which the customer has been with the bank

  • NumOfProducts: refers to the number of products that a customer has purchased through the bank.

  • Balance: Account balance

  • HasCrCard: It is a categorical variable which decides whether the customer has credit card or not.

  • EstimatedSalary: Estimated salary

  • isActiveMember: Is is a categorical variable which decides whether the customer is active member of the bank or not ( Active member in the sense, using bank products regularly, making transactions etc )

  • Exited : whether or not the customer left the bank within six month. It can take two values

** 0=No ( Customer did not leave the bank ) ** 1=Yes ( Customer left the bank )

Analyzing the statistical summary of each column in order:

  • RowNumber is an identifier column with values between 1 and 100000. It is likely to be a running serial number that doesn't add any meaning to the data. This column can be removed.
  • CustomerId is also an identifier column with IDs between 15565701 and 15815690. Though this is an important column for the business to identify the customer, it isn't necessarily useful for model building because each row has a unique ID, and the ID doesn't have any numerical value. This column can be removed as well.
  • Surname is an object column with 2932 unique values, with the most common ones being Smith, Martin, Scott, Walker, and Brown, and the least common ones being Aguirre and Morales, among others. While again, this a useful column to identify the customer, the people with the same surname could be related, but it is unlikely that all 32 Smiths are related, especially with some common surnames appearing in the database. It is not likely a very useful column for analysis. This column can also be removed for our prediction,
  • CreditScore describes the customer's credit history. On average, customers have a credit score of 650, with a range between 350 and 850. Since the median 652 is very close to the mean and the min and max aren't too far away from the 1st and 3rd quartile, it is likely more or less normally distributed.
  • Geography is a categorical variable with only 3 unique counts. 5014 customers are in France, 2509 of them are in Germany, and 2477 are in Spain.
  • Gender is also a categorical variable with values of Male and Female. 5457 customers are male, and 4543 are female.
  • The values in the column Age range between 18 and 92, which is quite a large range. On average, the customer's age is 39, and the median is 37. 75% of the customers are 44 years old or less, which means the data could be a little right-skewed.
  • Tenure describes the number of years the customer has been with the bank. On average, a customer has been with the bank for 5 years, ranging between 0 and 10.
  • Balance describes the customer's account balance. The average balance is 76485, whereas the median is 97198, with the max going all the way to 250898, which indicates possible right skewness and many outliers.
  • NumOfProducts; On average a customer has 1.5 products with a range of 1 to 4.
  • HasCrCard is an encoded variable with values 0 or 1 indicating whether a customer has a credit card or not. It can be treated as a categorical variable, and we will examine its distribution in the univariate analysis.
  • IsActiveMember is also an encoded categorical variable with values of 0 or 1 indicating whether a customer is an active member or nor.
  • The average estimated salary of a customer is 100090, with a minimum of 11.58 and a maximum of 199992.48, which shows quite a massive range.
  • Exited is our target variable, which indicates whether a customer has left or is still with the bank. Its values are 0 and 1.

# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.


def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a triangle will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

# function to plot stacked bar chart

def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart

    data: dataframe
    predictor: independent variable
    target: target variable
    """
    count = data[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True).sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 120)
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left", frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()

### Function to plot distributions

def distribution_plot_wrt_target(data, predictor, target):

    fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 10))

    target_uniq = data[target].unique()

    axs[0, 0].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[0]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[0]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 0],
        color="teal",
    )

    axs[0, 1].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[1]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[1]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 1],
        color="orange",
    )

    axs[1, 0].set_title("Boxplot w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=target, y=predictor, ax=axs[1, 0], palette="gist_rainbow")

    axs[1, 1].set_title("Boxplot (without outliers) w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data,
        x=target,
        y=predictor,
        ax=axs[1, 1],
        showfliers=False,
        palette="gist_rainbow",
    )

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Univariate Analysis¶

CreditScore¶

In [ ]:
histogram_boxplot(data, "CreditScore")
  • The Credit Score is slightly left-skewed but mostly normally distributed, with some outliers below the first quartile. However, there are a significant number of customers in the highest credit score bracket, which balances out the distribution.
  • The mean and median credit score is around 650.
  • 75% of the customers have a credit score of around 720 or less.

Geography¶

In [ ]:
labeled_barplot(data, "Geography", perc=True)
  • The geography column has three regions. Half of the customers are in France, and the other half are nearly equally distributed between Germany and Spain.
  • 50.1% of customers are in France, 25.1% in Germany and 24.8% in Spain.

Gender¶

In [ ]:
labeled_barplot(data, "Gender", perc=True)
  • The customers consist of more Males than Females.
  • 54.6% of the customers are male and 45.4% female. They are evenly distributed overall, making gender a suitable variable for prediction.

Age¶

In [ ]:
histogram_boxplot(data, "Age")
  • The age of the customers has a very wide range, with many outliers towards the right.
  • As suspected, the data is right-skewed with outliers above the age of 60. The mean age is around 39, and the median age is around 37. This value is very far from the outliers that go all the way up to 92.
  • 50% of the customers are aged between 32 and 44.
  • There is a spike of customers who are all in their late 20s, possibly around 28-29, and there is another even higher spike at age around 39.

Tenure¶

In [ ]:
labeled_barplot(data, "Tenure", perc=True)
  • Though Tenure is a numerical value, it is a discrete variable with numbers from 0 to 10.
  • About 10% of customers fall into each of the tenures of 1 to 9 years, which is fairly evenly distributed, whereas the remaining 10% is nearly equally distributed between 0 and 10 years.
  • 4.1% of New customers have been with the bank for 0 years, and 4.9% of customers have a tenure of 10 years.
  • The balanced tenure spread across most categories allows us to perform potentially useful model building to predict our target variable.

Balance¶

In [ ]:
histogram_boxplot(data, "Balance")
  • Balance distribution is right-skewed owing to the large number of customers with a balance of 0.
  • The customers with a zero balance may be new or inactive.
  • There are very high customers with a high balance, and 75% of the customers have a balance of about 12750 or less.

NumOfProducts¶

In [ ]:
labeled_barplot(data, "NumOfProducts", perc= True)
  • 50.8% of the customers have one product with the bank, while 45.9% have two. Between them, they cover over 96% of the customers.
  • 2.7% of the customers have three products.
  • Only 60 customers have 4 products.
  • The distribution isn't very even, but it might be helpful to see whether there is any behaviour related to customers with 1 or 2 products and their likelihood to churn.

HasCrCard¶

In [ ]:
labeled_barplot(data, "HasCrCard", perc=True)
  • 29.4% of the customers do not have a credit card, while 70.5% of them do. This isn't very evenly distributed between the two groups, but there are enough customers in both groups for the column to be valuable.

Utility functions¶

In [ ]:
# Function to create a plot with desired metric like loss and recall
def plot(history, name):
    """
    Function to plot loss/recall

    history: an object which stores the metrics and losses.
    name: can be one of Loss or Recall
    """
    fig, ax = plt.subplots() #Creating a subplot with figure and axes.
    plt.plot(history.history[name]) #Plotting the train recall or train loss
    plt.plot(history.history['val_'+name]) #Plotting the validation recall or validation loss

    plt.title('Model ' + name.capitalize()) #Defining the title of the plot.
    plt.ylabel(name.capitalize()) #Capitalizing the first letter.
    plt.xlabel('Epoch') #Defining the label for the x-axis.
    fig.legend(['Train', 'Validation'], loc="outside right upper") #Defining the legend, loc controls the position of the legend.
In [ ]:
# Custom confusion matrix function
def make_confusion_matrix(actual_targets, predicted_targets):
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix with percentages

    actual_targets: actual target (dependent) variable values
    predicted_targets: predicted target (dependent) variable values
    """
    cm = confusion_matrix(actual_targets, predicted_targets)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(cm.shape[0], cm.shape[1])

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")

Model Building¶

Model Evaluation Criterion¶

In this case we are doing a churn classification problem and the false predictions can be of two types:

  1. False positives: When a customer is not going to exit but the model predicted that they would, which may lead to unnecessary retention effort costs.
  2. False negatives: When a customer is going to exit but the model predicted that they wouldn't, which translates to potential revenue loss.

The cost to the bank of missing a customer who churned is much greater than if they accidentally mark a customer as going to churn when they aren't. The difference is between losing a customer they didn't mark as risk of churn v/s being overly pessimistic about certain customers. The cost of losing a customer is much higher than spending resources on targeted retention of a few extra customers. Hence, we want to reduce false negatives and will focus on getting the best Recall

In [ ]:
# Plotting train vs validation loss
plot(history_0,'loss')

The graph shows the value of the loss function over 50 epochs for both the training and validation sets.

  • As expected, both training and validation losses decrease as the number of epochs increases, indicating that the model is learning and the predictions are improving.
  • The training loss (blue line) decreases steadily throughout the training process. It starts relatively high around 0.55 and then drops significantly during the first 10 epochs, showing that the model quickly learns key patterns from the training data. After around 30 epochs, the training loss continues to decrease, but at a slower rate, indicating the model is converging.
  • The validation loss (orange line) also decreases initially, following a similar trend to the training loss. The validation loss plateaus at a higher value than train, stabilizing after around 20 epochs, which suggests that the model has learned the general patterns in the data without overfitting
  • The training loss continues to decrease and is a little lower than the validation loss. Since the validation loss doesn't increase significantly, there is no sign of overfitting and since the loss isn't too far off from the training, it generalizes fairly well.
In [ ]:
# Plotting train vs validation recall
plot(history_0,'recall')

The graph shows the value of the recall metric over 50 epochs for both the training and validation sets.

  • Both training and validation recall increase sharply within the first 10 epochs indicating a lot of learning early on.
  • Recall on the training set continues to increase steadily, reaching about 0.5 at the end of the training.
  • Recall on the validation set also increases steadily and starts the plateau with only marginal improvements after 20 epochs but don't reach the same recall as training.
  • The gap in the recall between the two sets is not alarming since they are close. However, given that the recall we reach is only around 0.5, that means we inaccurately classify 50% of the customers who will churn. Hence we do need to optimize the neural networks in different ways to achieve a better result.

This serves as a good base model.

From the two classification reports, we can observe the following:

  • In the training set, we get an accuracy of 0.87 but only a 0.47 recall, with a higher recall for the non churn clients.
  • In the validation set, there is an identical pattern of high accuracy and precision but lower recall especially for the churn clients.
  • The differences in the metrics between Class 0 and 1 could be due to imbalance in the classes in the Exited variable.

The graph shows the value of the loss function over 50 epochs for both the training and validation sets.

  • As expected, both training and validation losses decrease as the number of epochs increases, indicating that the model is learning and the predictions are improving.
  • The training loss (blue line) decreases steadily throughout the training process. It starts a little lower than the SGD optimizer, around 0.475, and then drops significantly during the first 5 epochs, showing that the model quickly learns key patterns from the training data. The model continues to learn, and the loss continues to decrease, but at a slower rate.
  • The validation loss (orange line) also decreases initially sharply, following a similar trend to the training loss. However, there is an unusual pattern of increase in the loss function for the validation data. It doesn't go back to the original loss value, but as the number of epochs increases, it actually diverges from the training loss.
  • The gap between the two is increasing steadily, so the model isn't generalizing well enough and may be capturing some noise.
In [ ]:
# Plotting train vs validation recall
plot(history_1,'recall')

The graph shows the value of the recall metric over 50 epochs for both the training and validation sets.

  • Both training and validation recall increase sharply within the first 5 or so epochs, indicating quick learning early on.
  • Recall on the training set continues to increase steadily, reaching a higher score of about 0.6 at the end of the training.
  • Recall on the validation set already increases steadily and starts to plateau with only marginal improvements after 10 or so epochs but is quite unstable with the increase and decrease in epoch. There are very small fluctuations.
  • The gap in the recall between the two sets is significant and may indicate that the model hasn't learned well enough to perform on unseen data. However, given that the recall we reach is still only around 0.6, that means we inaccurately classify 40% of the customers who will churn. Hence, we need to optimize the neural networks in different ways to achieve an even better result.

The graph shows the value of the loss function over 50 epochs for both the training and validation sets.

  • As expected, both training and validation losses decrease as the number of epochs increases, indicating that the model is learning and the predictions are improving.
  • The training loss (blue line) decreases steadily throughout the training process. It starts around around 0.48 and then drops significantly during the first 5 epochs, showing that the model quickly learns key patterns from the training data. The model continues to learn and the loss continues to decrease at a slower rate with visible fluctuations as the number of epochs increases, however still with an overall reduction.
  • The validation loss (orange line) also decreases initially sharply, following a similar trend to the training loss. The validation loss seems more stable than training loss and converges very quickly with almost no fluctuation or decrease after 10 or so epochs.
  • The gap between the two is minor but exists because of the fluctuations of the training set loss.

The graph shows the value of the recall metric over 50 epochs for both the training and validation sets.

  • Both training and validation recall increase sharply within the first 5 or so epochs indicating rapid learning early on.
  • Recall on the training set continues to increase steadily, reaching a score of about 0.45 at the end of the training with many fluctuations and instability after 10 or so epochs.
  • Recall on the validation set already increases steadily and then increases marginally with a lot of instability after 10 epochs with many apparent fluctuations.
  • The gap in the recall between the two sets is nearly constant within the fluctuations that both display and they are fairly close to each other.
  • However, given that the recall we reach is still only around 0.45, we haven't seen any significant improvement in adding a dropout layer to this model and also the instability of the learning is of concern.

# Plotting train vs validation loss
plot(history_4,'loss')
  • The training loss (blue line) decreases consistently throughout the 50 epochs, indicating that the model is continuously learning from the data. The Adam optimizer seems to be effectively minimizing the loss on training data.

*The validation loss (orange line) decreases initially but then begins to increase after about 5 epochs and continuing to rise over all the remaining epochs.

  • The model is performing well on training data but is not able to generalize on the validation data, which indicates overfitting. This means that the model is likely learning the noise in the data and is unable to predict on unseen data.
  • As expected, both training and validation losses decrease as the number of epochs increases, indicating that the model is learning and the predictions are improving.
In [ ]:
# Plotting train vs validation recall
plot(history_4,'recall')
  • Recall on the training set starts at a high value and continues to increase steadily, which means the model is learning well and finishes close to 0.90 recall.
  • On the other hand, recall on the validation set starts at around 0.70 and shows fluctuations and a even a slightly downward trend from epoch onwards.
  • The difference in recall between the validation and training set is significant and consistently remains large, which again indicates overfitting and how even though the training data is learning better, the model is still unable to predict well on the validation data.
  • The model is likely learning noise that doesn't predict well in the validation set. It is possible that the oversampled data has amplified some data points with noise which is being learnt in the training set and not applicable to unseen data.

plot(history_5,'recall')
  • Recall on the training set starts at around 0.66 and increases rapidly in the first 10 epochs and then increases more slowly and with fluctuations until it reaches a recall of around 0.78.
  • Recall on the validation dataset also increases initially but then continues to fall and stabilizes around 0.69.
  • The model is not performing as well on unseen data and it is on training data, and the fluctuations in validation recall indicates that the model is unable to generalize well enough from the traiing to validation set.
  • The model is likely overfitting, however it is an improvement from the previous model with much higher overfitting.

Below is a concise summary of comparison of recalls of all the models between train and validaton datasets

  • NN with SGD: Low recall in both train and validation data
  • NN with Adam: Low recall but improved over SGD, with significant gap between the train and validation
  • NN with Adam and Dropout: Lower recall compared to without dropout
  • NN with SMOTE and SGD: Much improved performance after oversampling
  • NN with SMOTE and Adam: Increased recall but large gap between train and validation, which is a clear sign of overfitting
  • NN with SMOTE, Adam and Dropout: Lower recall but fluctuating recall values which also indicates overfitting, though improved over the model without dropout.

Considering all the recall comparisons here and also the recall over epochs, the chosen model is NN with SMOTE and SGD because it is good at generalizing, isn't overfitting, and despite the small difference between train and validation recall, the learning and predicting power is much more stable.

Actionable Insights and Business Recommendations¶

Based on the exploratory data analysis, model building, model performance improvement attempts, and overall analysis, the following are recommendations for the business:

  • With a recall of about 0.67 on unseen data, the model correctly identifies 67% of the customers that churn. The business must focus on this group to implement retention strategies like targeted marketing and focused customer service because these customers are likely to churn.
  • Being able to identify a large number of customers likely to churn means the business can further study these customers and their characteristics, such as tenure, activity, and account balance, for personalized retention strategies and possibly even clustering analysis.
  • Further areas of exploration for the model can include experimenting with other optimization strategies, such as L1/L2 regularization, weight initialization, etc., to further reduce overfitting and potentially improve recall.
  • It is worthwhile investing in continuing to collect data and more features for further analysis to rectify the model's current limitations. Exploring other features, such as the custom satisfaction score from the survey, activity in the last quarter, the number of points of contact with the bank, etc., may improve the model's generalization power.
  • Since customers' behaviour is likely to change over time, it is important to continuously retrain the model at regular intervals with updated data and maintain it up to date with new customer behaviour so that it continues to be useful and relevant.

Based on these insights, the company can implement particular actions to enhance retention rates and reduce churn and also develop the predictive model in the long term. From the technology perspective, a data-driven approach and constant improvement of the model will help the company proactively implement measures against churn and retain the existing customer base.
